\section{Section Three}
\label{sec:three}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{\protect\numberline{\thechapter.\thesection}Section Three}

\section{Section Four}
\label{sec:four}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{\protect\numberline{\thechapter.\thesection}Section Four}

\end{document}
```

In this example, we first include the `\tableofcontents` command in the document. Then, we define different chapters and sections using the `\chapter` and `\section` commands. To add these chapters and sections to the TOC, we use the `\addcontentsline` command. This command requires three arguments: `toc` (which specifies the file to add the line to), the type of entry (in this case, `chapter` or `section`), and the text to be displayed in the TOC.

Note that we use the `\protect` command to protect the `\numberline` command from being expanded during the addition of the line to the TOC. We also use `\thechapter` and `\thesection` to get the current chapter and section numbers, respectively.

To draw a chessboard in LATEX, you can use the `xskak` package, which is a LaTeX package that can be used to draw chessboards and pieces. Here's an example of how you can do it:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage[material]{xskak}

\begin{document}

\newchessboard*

\mainline{\fenboard{rnbqkbnr/ppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR}}

\end{document}
```

In this example, `\newchessboard*` is used to define a new chessboard, and `\mainline{\fenboard{rnbqkbnr/ppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR}}` is used to specify the starting position of the game. The FEN notation (rnbqkbnr/ppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR) is used to specify the current state of the board, including the pieces and their positions.

The `xskak` package uses a 0-based indexing system for rows and columns, so the top-left square is (0,0) and the bottom-right square is (7,7). The pieces are represented by the following characters:

- 'R' for rook
- 'N' for knight
- 'B' for bishop
- 'Q' for queen
- 'K' for king
- 'p' for pawn
- 'P' for pawn (black)
- '/' for empty square
- '8' for empty row

To draw a board with a different state, you can simply replace the FEN notation in the `\mainline` command with a new FEN notation.

For example, here's a LATEX code that draws a board with a king and pawn on each side:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage[material]{xskak}

\begin{document}

\newchessboard*

\mainline{\fenboard{rk1pq1r/1ppp1PPP/8/8/8/8/1PPPP1PP/RK1Q1R1}}

\end{document}
```

This code will draw a board with a king and pawn on the first rank of each side, and empty rows and columns in between.

